          <a href="http://www.dea.gov/pubs/pressrel/pr072204.html">http://www.dea.gov/pubs/pressrel/pr072204.html</a>  Seems that the rules concerning drug analouges are now being enforced. This is a predictable new development. After reading the press release, to be honest, I actually support the action by the DEA. Drug analogous are <i>dangerous</i>. I would accuse these merchants of being horribly reckless, because they in no way whatsoever at all were honest about the dangers of their products. The product descriptions consisted of "a picture of a molecule". While I have some very libertanian leanings about product liabilities for dangerous stuff, I think it should none-the-less at least be clearly marked that such things are almost certainly untested safety-wise, and potentially quite lethal when used outside of a labroatory. For example, one of the products at WWW.RACREASEARCH.COM was "5-MeO-AMT". Information on this substance can be obtained from the psychoactive library of Erowid [<a href="http://www.erowid.org/">www.erowid.org</a>]. "5-MeO-AMT", short for 5-methoxy-alpha-methyl-tryptamine, is active at the ludicrously low dosage of 1mg! [<a href="http://www.erowid.org/chemicals/5meo_amt/5meo_amt_dose.shtml">http://www.erowid.org/chemicals/5meo_amt/5meo_amt_dose.shtml</a>] Such a small amount can ONLY be safely measured in a chemistry lab, on a high-grade milligram-accurate scale, which incidentally cost roughly somewhere between $1500 and $2000. A dosage as low as 30mg is extremely dangerous.<br /><blockquote><br />a review of customer lists revealed purchasers  with e-mail addresses such as acidtripo420@; ecstasylight@; madtriper17@; moontripperdipt@; partys_with_glow_sticks@; professor@; psychedelic_stoner@;  and ravergirlny@.<br /></blockquote><br />It is patently obvious from the customer list that these buyers had no legitimate reaserch interest.<br /><br /><br />
