     <font class="TallRed">How bad was your childhood?<a name="109090014891080839">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          Man, you never really realize how bad your childhood is until you find yourself rambling to a coworker about how screwy your parents are. I left my sister 4-5 years ago with them and the amount of damage done is...appauling.  Have you ever had a day dream where you are back at your house, you can't leave, there's nothing particularly wrong and yet nothing is quite right. You awaken to find yourself sweating and standing in someone else's office. <span style="font-style: italic;">Hmm, perhaps I began day dreaming while walking somewhere and now I'm in this person's office and they're just looking at me strangely. </span><br /> <br /> How annoying is it trying to tell a sick person to just hurry up and get well? Very annoying. My sister seems to be suffering from manic depression and high school (yes, I used high school as an example of illness). She's one of those people who think that Goths have a purpose and that most of them are smart. She even went so far to offend me today by saying McGruff the Crime Dog, the top dawg I work for, is stupid. I told her, "I'll bet you 200$ that in 10 years not only will those people not dress in black anymore, but they will be working for the National Crime Prevention Council." My uncle is trying to come up with excuses on why she acts the ways she does and he always comes to the conlusion I came up with yesterday after doing some time researching.<br /> <br /> Sometimes I believe that my parents are doing a royal job of screwing her up without even knowing it. Or she is just going through adolescense and is not as mature as I was when I was the same age. She thinks school is dumb and after she's out the world is just a playground. Well, I says to her, "it is sorta like a play ground". I rub my chin, then continue: <blockquote>Me: Yes, life is sorta like a playground.<br /> BT: it is?<br /> Me: well, life is like one of those slides you see at many playgrounds nowadays where the entire structure looks friendly on the outside because its made of soft plastic but when you are using it you always feel like everything is going too fast and every once in a while you collect too much static and it shocks the hell out of you. Once you reach the end, your hair is on end and you're very stressed out. People never stop throwing sand. Sexuality is like the swingset, some people are this way, some people are that way, and some people just like to sit in them and watch everyone else. If you're daring you check out the spinning wheel of doom. People like getting a rush out of that; there's always blood smeared somewhere on it. Some kids like to sit in the middle and slowly work their way into the pull of inertia, and some kids like to try to jump in later on, only to get knocked the <span style="font-style: italic;">fuck</span> out by the spinning metal bars. <br /> BT: this all means something, doesn't it</blockquote> I tried, at least. She gets joy out of hearing about people's pain, constantly curses in replacement for actual meaningful words, and always changes the subject in conversation to be negative, dark, painfully dreadful. When trying to find out things she enjoys doing I mentioned that I write short stories every now and again so when I mentioned that one of the titles was "Superhuman Suicide" her ears suddenly perked up. I will continue to try to help open her eyes that the world was a place meant for her to conquer and that there is room for more emotions than just dry, dark, and gross humor. But don't get me wrong, the dry, dark, and gross humor certainly has it's place.<br /> <br /> So I didn't have the best of lives when I was younger. So I have stories that many will never hear. So...what? I told BT that in the end it all adds to the irony. If my parents weren't total wackjobs then what would I have to overcome? In every good story there is something large to overcome and in my story I had to overcome 1. my fears 2. my parents 3. myself. I have already accomplished so much, and have so many things on my resume and so many more things to do before I'm gone.  Are you still a little screwy from your f'd up childhood? Share with us, comments are open.<br /> <br /> Oh, and by the way, the secret number of the day is a low <span style="font-weight: bold;">9</span>.<br /> <br />
